Percentage of nuage-forming cells in 3âˆ† background Ede1 truncation mutants

Last compiled on March 21, 2022

Experiment

Rationale

I want to quantify the nuage-forming tendencies of each Ede1 truncation construct, in two yeast cell backgrounds (wild-type and apl3âˆ† yap1801âˆ† yap1802âˆ†) Absent a more finely tuned method, I have counted the percentage of condensate-containing cells (by subjective but blinded assessment).

Method

I acquired all data on the Olympus IX81 equipped with a 100x/1.49 objective, using the X-Cite 120PC lamp at 50% intensity and 400 ms exposure for illumination. Light was filtered through a U-MGFPHQ filter cube. I acquired stacks of 26 planes with a step size of 0.2 microns.

Individual cells were cropped out of fields of view based only on the bright field channel. I used the ImageJ macro blindAnalysis to sequentially display all images at random, blinding me to the strain of origin, and recording a binary decision about condensate formation for each image.

Plots

Lineplot

This is a difficult plot because of the number of variables involved: Ede1 truncation, strain background & dataset. First all on one plot, and means as thick lines.

Bar graph

The lines here do not provide enough visual cues as to which mean and point belongs to which combination of groups. As disliked as bar graphs are, I think in this case they would be much better suited to guide the reader.

Faceted line plot

Finally, for the easily confused (by multiple groupings) and the easily offended (by bar graphs), go back to lines but facet the two backgrounds.
